# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1950-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The **1950 Nippon Professional Baseball season** was the first season for baseball in Japan that used the new two league format since the split the previous year.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1950-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The two leagues would be known as the Central League and the Pacific League.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1951-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The **1951 Nippon Professional Baseball season** was the second season of operation of Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB).
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1951-nippon-professional-baseball-season] 1951 saw the best season in terms of winning percentage in NPB history, with the Nankai Hawks going 72-24-8, good enough for a .750 winning percentage, on their way to their first Japan Series appearance in franchise history.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1951-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The Yomiuri Giants would defeat the Nankai Hawks in the Japan Series 4 games to 1, marking the first of 22 Japan Series championships for the Giants.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1952-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The **1952 Nippon Professional Baseball season** was the third season of operation of Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB).
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1952-nippon-professional-baseball-season] For the first time, the Pacific League implemented a type of end-of-season playoff system.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1952-nippon-professional-baseball-season] After the 108-game regular season, the four teams with the best winning percentages played an extra twelve regular season games to determine the league's champion.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1952-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The four qualifying teams were the Nankai Hawks, the Mainichi Orions, the Nishitetsu Lions, and the Daiei Stars.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1952-nippon-professional-baseball-season] These four teams proceeded to play in a twelve game "round-robin" stage, with three games versus each opponent, in late September and early October.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1952-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The Mainichi Orions' won ten of the twelve extra games, which put them into a tie for the first place with the Nankai Hawks.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1952-nippon-professional-baseball-season] Both teams had 75 wins, however the Hawks had one less loss than the Orions because of a game against the Daiei Stars that ended in a tie earlier in the season.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1952-nippon-professional-baseball-season] Because of the impact the tie had on the pennant race, the Hawks and the Stars played an extra 121st game.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1952-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The Hawks won the game, giving them sole claim to Pacific League title.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1952-nippon-professional-baseball-season] After the season, this faux playoff system was scrapped because of criticism that it was unfair to the three non-qualifying teams that had their seasons truncated.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1953-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The **1953 Nippon Professional Baseball season** was the fourth season of operation of Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB).
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1953-nippon-professional-baseball-season] That season would be the first to be televised on the young NHK General TV - which opened that year.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1953-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The young channel and its then few national relay stations aired some games during the year, tying baseball to the young TV industry and thus beginning the sports connection to Japanese television, as well as its transformation into the top sport of the nation.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1954-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The **1954 Nippon Professional Baseball season** was the fifth season of operation of Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB).
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1955-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The **1955 Nippon Professional Baseball season** was the sixth season of operation of Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB).
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1955-nippon-professional-baseball-season] This season featured the worst statistical season by winning percentage in NPB history, a .231 winning percentage set by the Taiyo Whales.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1955-nippon-professional-baseball-season] This season also saw the most wins in a single season by a single team in NPB history, with the Nankai Hawks winning a record 99 games.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1955-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The Yomiuri Giants defeated the Nankai Hawks in the Japan Series, 4 games to 3, marking the Giants' 4th NPB championship, all of which to this point had come against the Hawks.
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1956-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The **1956 Nippon Professional Baseball season** was the seventh season of operation of Nippon Professional Baseball (NPB).
[src:1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season/1984-nippon-professional-baseball-season] The **1984 Nippon Professional Baseball season** was the 35th season of operation for the league.
